# Backend Conventions

## API design

- RESTful endpoints, resource-oriented
- URL paths in **kebab-case**: `/user-profiles`, `/order-items`
- Use correct HTTP verbs:
  | Verb     | Purpose              |
  |----------|----------------------|
  | `GET`    | Read (no side effect)|
  | `POST`   | Create               |
  | `PUT`    | Full replace         |
  | `PATCH`  | Partial update       |
  | `DELETE` | Remove               |
- Return appropriate status codes: `201` for creation, `204` for deletion, `400`/`422` for validation errors, `404` for not found, `500` only for unexpected errors
- Consistent JSON response shape across all endpoints

## Error handling

- Always return an explicit HTTP status code with a structured error body
- NEVER expose stack traces, internal paths, or implementation details in responses
- Map domain errors to HTTP errors at the infrastructure layer, not in the domain

## Configuration and secrets

- All sensitive values (API keys, DB credentials, tokens) go in environment variables
- NEVER hardcode secrets in source code
- Provide a `.env.example` with all required variables (no real values)

## Validation

- Validate all inputs at the boundary (controllers / route handlers in infrastructure)
- Business rule validation belongs in the domain layer
- Return clear error messages indicating which field failed and why

## Structure reminder

Follow the clean-architecture rule: controllers and routes live in `infrastructure/`, use cases in `application/`, business logic in `domain/`.
